    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Feature description\n\nAt the moment the `@combined` capture is handled per query, meaning that it does not behave as one may expect when used in more complex queries. For example with a query\r\n\r\n```\r\n[\r\n  (node1) @lang @combined\r\n  (node2) @lang\r\n]\r\n```\r\n\r\nand a tree\r\n\r\n```\r\n(node1)\r\n(node2)\r\n(node1)\r\n```\r\n\r\nall nodes would be parsed combined.\r\n\r\nIt is not clear and not documented what should happen in this example so it is not really a bug. Also I don't know of a tree-sitter grammar that currently uses this kind of query. I still propose that nodes that have the `@combined` capture should get parsed together with previous node. This would mean that in the given example the first node is parsed by itself and the second and third regions are combined.\r\n\r\nThis implementation would enable queries for which only *some* of the matches should be combined. In particular this would be useful for https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter/issues/2212.\r\n\r\nI'm also willing to implement this myself, but I wanted to ask before investing time since I've not yet contributed to neovim.",
    "closed_at": "2023-12-25T08:35:41Z",
